1. e4 {Hello and welcome to our course! The idea of surprising the opponent at an early stage has always been attractive to many players. However, this surprise should adhere to the following criteria:   - Drag the opponent to an unknown territory.   - Have a main idea (or a trap) that enables us to fight for an advantage.   - Be sound!   The 2. b3 Sicilian fulfils all these conditions. There are basically no traps (or at least no early traps) that secure the win for White. Instead, this is a strategical line where the first player intends to get his/her types of positions. Some of the arising middlegames are sharp, while some are more quiet. As it is the case in most openings, the structure of the battle is decided by how both sides position themselves. So even though White gets in the 'first decider', Black has lots of different ways to shape the game. Therefore, before starting to play the b3 Sicilian in serious games, we advise you to cover all the lines first. This opening is very rich when you take into account the range of possible position types.} c5 2. b3 {Developing the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal is one of the main ways to avoid 'Open Sicilian' lines. This move has been increasing in popularity lately due to its flexible nature. The game can take the form of a so called 'Open Game', but we can also find ourselves in one of the typical 'Closed Sicilian' territories. In this particular position, Black has several setups, and we will be examining all of them. As a pre-caution: this opening is still fresh  (as of early 2023) and theory has not reached its heights yet. Therefore you will be seeing lot of new stuff. Let's quickly point out all the possible variation that were played by masters and move on!} Nc6 {We could easily say that it is already time for Black to make a difficult decision. Of course, developing the knight can't be bad, and indeed it is one of the main moves. What we are trying to point out is that there are several possible setups for Black, and each move he makes leads to something different from now on.  As for White, it is obvious that the dark-squared bishop belongs on b2 , but what about the light-squared one? Sometimes it finds itself a place on the b5 -square (just like in the Rossolimo) , and sometimes White goes for a double fianchetto. Simple looking choices like these depend on the different setups that Black can play starting from move two!!} (2... g6 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 {is also very popular.}) (2... Nf6 {, d6 , b6 , e6 ,} 3. e5 {, and} d5 {are all options we'll consider.}) 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {One of the main lines of our interest. The battle begins! From now on White aims to create an environment in which the b2 -bishop reaches its peak, and for Black we can say that various counter plans are on the table. Some last words before getting into the theory chapters: There are quite a few transpositions possible, so the move order issue may get tricky. This 'small dance' is conducted by both sides, but we hope that players behind the white pieces will be much better prepared. So let's get started!   Selim Citak and Sabri Can Onay Yontar   İstanbul 2023} *

