1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 {Statistically speaking this is Black's most common reply. Black develops the knight to its natural square and prepares the move ... e5 to challenge the 'hero' on the long diagonal, which is very understandable.} 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {The fight for the e5 -square begins. White prefers the long diagonal to be open. After all, he made a challenging commitment on the second move!} e5 {Black has achieved his aim: to close down the b2 -bishop.} 5. f4 exf4 ({After} 5... Nf6 $6 6. fxe5 Nxe4 7. Nf3 d5 8. O-O {⩲ White has the semi-open f-file at his disposal. Therefore he should be able to claim a small advantage.}) 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. O-O Bd7 ({After} 7... Be7 8. e5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Qc7 10. Qf3 {White's pressure is starting to get annoying. Black only has one solution to this:} O-O {!} 11. Bxc6 (11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qxc6 Qb8 13. Bd3 {is also an option.}) 11... bxc6 12. Qxc6 Bd6 13. Qxc7 Bxc7 14. Nd3 Bf5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Na3 {Black's bishop pair compensates for his horrible pawn structure.}) 8. Nc3 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. Rxf4 {Regaining the pawn.} Qb6 (11... Nxd4 {is another one of Black's correct replies. Play might continue} 12. Qxd4 Bxb5 13. Nxb5 Rc8 14. Qd3 d5 15. e5 Ne4 16. Kh1 {White needs to step away from the problematic a7 - g1 diagonal.} Bg5 17. Rf3 {with an unclear game.}) 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Kh1 {Black has the bishop pair, but White has interesting attacking chances on the kingside. Involving the remaining pieces with Qd3 and Raf1 is obligatory.} *

