1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e6 {Black stays flexible with this move. It is not certain whether at some point he will play ... d5 or not.} 4. Nf3 {This is the most common move and also our recommendation. White can change the course of the opening by playing d2 - d4 anytime. Black now has four -seemingly logical- moves.} d6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {This position is very similar to the newly named 'Carlsen Sicilian'. If allowed, White can go Nc3 - Qd2 and O-O-O .} Nf6 7. Nc3 (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bxe5 {is a solid way of playing.}) 7... Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O {White has a great version (several tempi up) of Carlsen's set-up.} *

