1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e5 {Black has supported this pawn push with 2... Nc6 and now executes it. More often than not, we will find ourselves in a struggle where Black tries to shut down the b2 -bishop in this fashion. Right at this moment, White should plan for the future and play for f2 - f4 ideas to free the main guy.} 4. Bc4 d6 5. Ne2 {Developing the knight to e2 is consistent with our main plan: Pushing f4 at the right moment!} Nf6 6. Nbc3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. f4 exf4 {Analysis show that succumbing to pressure so easily is a mistake. Not only is the f-file opened for White's rook, but White also increases his control over the d5 -square.} 9. Nxf4 Ne5 10. d3 Nfg4 {Black's idea is to create counterplay on the dark squares.} 11. Ncd5 Bg5 12. Qe1 Bd7 13. a4 Re8 14. Bb5 {Disturbing Black's coordination.} Bc6 (14... Bxb5 15. axb5 Nf6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Nd5 Nf3+ 18. Rxf3 Bxb2 19. Rd1 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 {With such a powerful knight on d5 , playing this position won't be much of an issue for White.}) 15. h3 Nf6 16. Ne3 {Intending Nf5 , Qg3 , Rae1 . White has a strong attack.} *

