[ECO "B20"]
[PlyCount "21"]

1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 {Statistically speaking this is Black's most common reply. Black develops the knight to its natural square and prepares the move ... e5 to challenge the 'hero' on the long diagonal, which is very understandable.} 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {The fight for the e5 -square begins. White prefers the long diagonal to be open. After all, he made a challenging commitment on the second move!} e5 {Black has achieved his aim: to close down the b2 -bishop.} 5. f4 Nge7 {The only way to go for Black if he decides to decline the pawn. Actually, he will be offering one himself in one of the lines.} 6. Nf3 a6 ({Black's pawn sac occurs after} 6... g6 7. fxe5 Bg7 8. Bc3 O-O 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. Na3 $1 {An important move to remember: White's knight wants to get closer to the main action with tempo. Black can reply in two ways:} ({A) Bg4} 11. O-O Nd4 12. Be2 {Black has some compensation for the pawn, but White is very solid. Or} f5 {Nc4 Qd8 Bxc6 Nxc6} 13. exf5 {Nd4! Nce5} {Rxf5?? Ne3+-} Nxf3+ {Nxf3 Rxf5 and Black has enough compensation for the missing pawn.}) ({B) Striking the center immediately with f5 is worth mentioning. Nc4 Qd8} 11. e5 g5 $1 {Black needs to continue with this move as otherwise 11... f5 would make no sense, and White would have a clear advantage. That this move is necessary shows us how difficult it can be to handle such positions. Play might continue} 12. O-O Ng6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. d3 {with a small edge for White.})) 7. Bxc6+ Nxc6 8. Nc3 {Now White gets to place the knight on d5 without any real issues.} g6 ({After} 8... Be6 $6 9. f5 Bd7 10. O-O Nd4 11. Nd5 Bc6 12. c4 {White will eventually end up with the better bishop once the exchange on d5 happens. Here} f6 $5 {is also a very interesting pawn sac. Bxd5 exd5 Nxf3+ Rxf3 gxf6} {gxf6? Nh4! ±} 13. Qe2 {and White has good compensation.}) 9. Nd5 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. d3 {If you play 2. b3 as White, you must be prepared to play such a position with chances for both sides. White's main trump is the f-file where he can apply some pressure on the opponent. His main ideas in the short term can be cementing the central knight with c4 and transferring the queen to the kingside.} ({After} 11. Z0 c4 {there is also the threat of} 12. Z0 f5 $1 {, since after the tactical sequence gxf5} 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 {Rxf5 the knight on d5 is now protected by the pawn on c4 .}) *

