1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 {Statistically speaking this is Black's most common reply. Black develops the knight to its natural square and prepares the move ... e5 to challenge the 'hero' on the long diagonal, which is very understandable.} 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {The fight for the e5 -square begins. White prefers the long diagonal to be open. After all, he made a challenging commitment on the second move!} e5 {Black has achieved his aim: to close down the b2 -bishop.} 5. f4 exf4 ({After} 5... Nf6 $6 6. fxe5 Nxe4 7. Nf3 d5 8. O-O {⩲ White has the semi-open f-file at his disposal. Therefore he should be able to claim a small advantage. Black can also play} Bg4 $5 {, intending ... Ng5 , which leads to double-edged play: O-O !} 9. Ng5 {exd6 Nxf3+ gxf3} Bh3 10. Re1 Kd7 11. Qe2 Bd6 12. Qf2 {with an unclear position.}) 6. Nf3 Nge7 {This has the idea to hang on the newly grabbed pawn, but it is insufficient for equality.} 7. O-O Ng6 (7... a6 8. Bxc6+ {Time is critical as in most cases.} Nxc6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Nd5 O-O 11. d3 {White has a nice pawn structure and can recover the pawn with Nxf4 at the right moment.}) 8. d4 {A different approach is necessary since regaining the pawn will not be easy after ... Ng6 .} Bd7 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nf5) 9. Nbd2 a6 {is too slow:} 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. d5 Bd7 12. e5 {White opens up the position while Black's king is still in the middle.} dxe5 13. Nxe5 f6 (13... Bd6 $2 14. Nxg6 hxg6 (14... fxg6 15. Nc4) 15. Bxg7 Rh7 16. Re1+ {and it's over.}) 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Nc4 {With Re1 + coming next, Black is busted. White can expect to get a quick victory in this position.} *

