1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 {Statistically speaking this is Black's most common reply. Black develops the knight to its natural square and prepares the move ... e5 to challenge the 'hero' on the long diagonal, which is very understandable.} 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {The fight for the e5 -square begins. White prefers the long diagonal to be open. After all, he made a challenging commitment on the second move!} e5 {Black has achieved his aim: to close down the b2 -bishop.} 5. f4 exf4 ({After} 5... Nf6 $6 6. fxe5 Nxe4 7. Nf3 d5 8. O-O {⩲ White has the semi-open f-file at his disposal. Therefore he should be able to claim a small advantage. Black can also play} Bg4 $5 {, intending ... Ng5 , which leads to double-edged play: O-O !} 9. Ng5 {exd6 Nxf3+ gxf3} Bh3 10. Re1 Kd7 11. Qe2 Bd6 12. Qf2 {with an unclear position.}) 6. Nf3 Nge7 {This has the idea to hang on the newly grabbed pawn, but it is insufficient for equality.} 7. O-O Ng6 (7... a6 8. Bxc6+ {Time is critical as in most cases.} Nxc6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Nd5 O-O 11. d3 {White has a nice pawn structure and can recover the pawn with Nxf4 at the right moment.}) 8. d4 Be7 {An interesting try: Black wants to make use of the fact that, for the moment, the b2 -bishop does not attack the g7 -pawn. If the tactics do work in Black's favour (fortunately they don't!) castling with an extra pawn would be great.} 9. d5 a6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Bxg7 {Now Black's king will not be able to castle. Play along the g-file is Black's best hope.} Rg8 12. Bc3 cxd5 13. exd5 Bf5 {An important developing move ,not letting us play Qd3 .} (13... Kf8 14. Qd3 $1 Bh3 15. Ne1 Bg4 16. Nd2) 14. Qe2 Kf8 15. Nbd2 {Since Black's king has some safety issues, White must act quickly. Therefore sacrificing the c2 -pawn is called for. I will give two possible continuations:} ({A) Bxc2 Rae1 Bf5 Ne4 Now Nfd2 is a huge threat, which means Black must let go of the bishop pair. Bxe4} 15. Qe4 Bf6 16. Bd2 $1 Be5 17. g3 $1 {⩲ Defending this position with Black is extremely difficult in practice.}) ({B)} 15. Bf6 {Qc4 Kg7 Black's king has reached safety, solving some of Black's problems. The best White can now hope for is to get a better endgame. The following moves illustrate this aim: Rae1 Bxc3 Qxc3+ Qf6 Qxf6+ Kxf6 Ne4+} Be4 {Rxe4⩲ .}) *

