1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 {Statistically speaking this is Black's most common reply. Black develops the knight to its natural square and prepares the move ... e5 to challenge the 'hero' on the long diagonal, which is very understandable.} 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {The fight for the e5 -square begins. White prefers the long diagonal to be open. After all, he made a challenging commitment on the second move!} Nf6 {After this move White can create a position that is typical in Closed Sicilian lines.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. d3 e5 7. Ne2 g6 8. O-O Bh6 {This is a rare and interesting option for Black. We don't often get to see the bishop activated via the h6 -square once the g-pawn is pushed.} 9. f4 O-O 10. h3 {Preventing both ... Ng4 and ... Bg4 ideas. It is especially vital to deny the black knight jumping to g4 .} exf4 11. Nxf4 Ne8 {Preparing ... f5 seems like the most challenging idea for Black. We need to see how such tries should be met.} 12. Nd2 f5 13. e5 {Not allowing Black to open the f-file.} d5 14. Qe2 {White has the better pawn structure. One idea can be to focus on the weak c5 -pawn, combined with pushing the e5 -pawn further.} *

