1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 {Statistically speaking this is Black's most common reply. Black develops the knight to its natural square and prepares the move ... e5 to challenge the 'hero' on the long diagonal, which is very understandable.} 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {The fight for the e5 -square begins. White prefers the long diagonal to be open. After all, he made a challenging commitment on the second move!} Qc7 {is a rare move in master practice. Black wants to make sure that his pawn structure will stay intact. First player can safely continue by employing many various line-ups.} 5. f4 e6 6. Nf3 a6 {Some other possibilities:} (6... Bd7 {Black wants to endu p with a bishop on c6 .} 7. c4 a6 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Nc3 Nf6 10. d3 Be7 11. O-O {We get this type of position several times in this course, but repeating does not hurt: White firstly needs to play Qd2 and Rae1 and then prepare the f5 thrust.}) (6... Nf6 7. e5 {White accepts the challenge and changes the pawn structure.} Nd5 8. O-O {!} Be7 (8... Nxf4 $4 9. g3 Ng6 10. Ng5) 9. Ng5 $1 {As we can see after this energetic move, White has good prospects.} O-O 10. Qh5 Bxg5 11. Qxg5 dxe5 12. fxe5 Bd7 13. Na3) 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. d3 Nf6 9. O-O Be7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Qe1 {The most effective plan includes getting queen to g3 first and then fully completing the development with the ever useful move Rae1 . Depending on our opponent's reaction, we may consider an early e5 push.} *

