1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 {Statistically speaking this is Black's most common reply. Black develops the knight to its natural square and prepares the move ... e5 to challenge the 'hero' on the long diagonal, which is very understandable.} 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 {The fight for the e5 -square begins. White prefers the long diagonal to be open. After all, he made a challenging commitment on the second move!} Bd7 ({A much better move than} 4... Qc7 {, since after the exchange on c6 Black will end up with a useful bishop.}) 5. f4 {Further controlling the center, fighting for the e5 -square and also gaining an opportunity to play attacking chess thanks to the semi-open f-file in some variations.} a6 {Black's main reply, which forces White to decide the fate of the b5 -bishop. Since time matters in chess, especially in such a position where the game is bound to stay 'open', we will take on c6 .} 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nc3 (7. Qe2 {will transpose into the main line after} Nf6 8. Nc3 {.}) 7... e6 {It is useful to check Black's different options. As a quick note, both sides may still reach the mainline by this move order.} 8. Nf3 b5 ({Had Black just developed the knight with} 8... Nf6 {, we would be analyzing the main line. This is a bit different.}) 9. Qe2 Nf6 (9... b4 $6 {would not be ideal since it weakens the c4 -square.} 10. Nd1 Nf6 11. d3 Be7 12. Ne3 {seems like a much better version of the mainline for White.}) 10. e5 {Now Black has played b5 instead of Be7 . This small nuance should play into White's hands.} Nh5 11. Qe3 d5 12. d4 ({Black needs to be extremely careful not to stand much worse. For instance, in this particular position g6 is the only way to go. In case of} 12. b4 $2 {Ne2} g6 {dxc5 Ng7 Bd4 Nf5 Qd2± not only can White hold on to his extra pawn, but he also has strong ideas connected with the a2 - a3 pawn push.}) ({g6 dxc5} 12. d4 $1 {Again, the only move for Black to equalize. Qxd4 Qxd4 Nxd4 Bxg2 Rg1 Bxc5 Ncxb5! axb5 Rxg2} Nxf4 {Rf2 White might even consider an exchange sac by taking on b5 on the next move. This is a very sharp ending in which White is definitely not worse.}) *

