1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e6 {Black stays flexible with this move. It is not certain whether at some point he will play ... d5 or not.} 4. Nf3 {This is the most common move and also our recommendation. White can change the course of the opening by playing d2 - d4 anytime. Black now has four -seemingly logical- moves.} (4. Bb5 {, developing the second bishop, resembles the Rossolimo Systems, but it is not so effective here as Black has time to guard the knight immediately:} Nge7 $1 5. Ne2 (5. f4 {Playing with the f-pawn is double-edged here as White will need to concede the bishop pair.} a6 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. d3 d5 8. Nd2 d4 9. Ngf3 Be7) 5... a6 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. O-O b5 8. d3 Bb7 9. Nd2 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 (10... exd5 $2 11. Re1 {is out of question.}) 11. Nf4 Qf5 12. Nh5 $1 {∞ This position is hard to assess due to its unorthodox dynamics. White has a lead in development and some direct threats, whereas Black has the 'ever-famous' bishop pair.}) (4. f4 {is seen in the model game Morozevich-Gordievsky .}) 4... d6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {This position is very similar to the newly named 'Carlsen Sicilian'. If allowed, White can go Nc3 - Qd2 and O-O-O .} Nf6 7. Nc3 (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bxe5 {is a solid way of playing.}) 7... Be7 8. Qd2 Qb6 9. Nxc6 {White could have gone for a better endgame with 9.O- O-O , but keeping the queens on the board might create more problems for Black.} bxc6 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Kb1 Rd8 12. Bd3 {White's next move is likely to be g4 , and White is faster in setting up an attack on the enemy king.} *

