1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e6 {Black stays flexible with this move. It is not certain whether at some point he will play ... d5 or not.} 4. Nf3 {This is the most common move and also our recommendation. White can change the course of the opening by playing d2 - d4 anytime. Black now has four -seemingly logical- moves.} (4. Bb5 {, developing the second bishop, resembles the Rossolimo Systems, but it is not so effective here as Black has time to guard the knight immediately:} Nge7 $1 5. Ne2 (5. f4 {Playing with the f-pawn is double-edged here as White will need to concede the bishop pair.} a6 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. d3 d5 8. Nd2 d4 9. Ngf3 Be7) 5... a6 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. O-O b5 8. d3 Bb7 9. Nd2 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 (10... exd5 $2 11. Re1 {is out of question.}) 11. Nf4 Qf5 12. Nh5 $1 {∞ This position is hard to assess due to its unorthodox dynamics. White has a lead in development and some direct threats, whereas Black has the 'ever-famous' bishop pair.}) (4. f4 {is seen in the model game Morozevich-Gordievsky .}) 4... Nf6 {Black is teasing the opponent to push e5 with a tempo. White had better not duck the challenge!} 5. e5 Nd5 ({After} 5... Ng4 6. h3 Nh6 7. Nc3 d5 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Ne4 {White can claim a small edge once the bishop pair is gained.}) 6. g3 {This is kind of a novelty of our course, based on the master games played till middle of 2022. White's light-squared bishop has no real future on the f1 - a6 diagonal. Also note that the move g3 takes away the f4 -square from the black knight.} d6 (6... Be7 {is considered via a different move order in chapter 4 .}) 7. exd6 Qxd6 8. Na3 {We already see Black has some problems, as he cannot easily develop the bishop on f8 .} f6 9. Bg2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. d4 {White will keep pressuring the weak e6 -pawn, which cannot move easily due to the fragile situation of the knight on d5 . This sample line shows how pleasant it can be to play as White in this specific variation.} *

