1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e6 {Black stays flexible with this move. It is not certain whether at some point he will play ... d5 or not.} 4. Nf3 {This is the most common move and also our recommendation. White can change the course of the opening by playing d2 - d4 anytime. Black now has four -seemingly logical- moves.} (4. Bb5 {, developing the second bishop, resembles the Rossolimo Systems, but it is not so effective here as Black has time to guard the knight immediately:} Nge7 $1 5. Ne2 (5. f4 {Playing with the f-pawn is double-edged here as White will need to concede the bishop pair.} a6 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. d3 d5 8. Nd2 d4 9. Ngf3 Be7) 5... a6 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. O-O b5 8. d3 Bb7 9. Nd2 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 (10... exd5 $2 11. Re1 {is out of question.}) 11. Nf4 Qf5 12. Nh5 $1 {∞ This position is hard to assess due to its unorthodox dynamics. White has a lead in development and some direct threats, whereas Black has the 'ever-famous' bishop pair.}) (4. f4 {is seen in the model game Morozevich-Gordievsky .}) 4... a6 5. c4 {Since White is robbed of Bb5 ideas, placing another pawn in the center and changing the course of the game to a 'Maroczy Bind' seems like the best option.} d6 {This is not challenging.} (5... Qc7 {is a clever move that stops 6. d4 . This is a trap that we should be aware of:} 6. d4 $2 (6. g3 {was played in a game Romanov-Can, St. Petersburg 2013. After} d6 {White was able to play} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {and the game eventually ended in a draw.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qe5 $1 8. Bc3 Bb4 9. Ne2 Nf6 $1 {There was nothing wrong with grabbing the e4 -pawn, but developing a piece is even stronger. White is in huge trouble now, as his pieces lack coordination and it is not clear how he can complete development. For instance,} 10. f3 d5 11. Qd2 dxe4 12. Bxe5 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Nxe5 14. Nxe4 Nd3+ 15. Kd2 Nxe4+ 16. fxe4 Nf2) 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O {White will enjoy his space advantage for quite some time. Several ideas are possible of course, but we would suggest a set-up of Rc1 - Qd2 - Kh1 - f4 and Bf3 .} *

