o look for an edge.}) 6... Ng4 7. h3 Nh6 8. Nc3 d6 (8... Nf5 {tries to fight against White's d4 push. Now a different approach is called for:} 9. Bd3 Nfd4 10. Ne4 d5 $1 {Now the game gets a little sharper. Some wild tactics will occur and White needs to be prepared for them.} 11. exd6 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 f5 13. Nxc5 Qxd6 14. b4 {The only move, but it is enough to save the day.} Nxb4 15. a3 Nc6 (15... Nxd3+ $2 16. Nxd3 {with important control over the e5 -square.}) 16. Nb3 Ne5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5+ 18. Be2 Bd6 19. d4 Qf4 20. c5 Bc7 21. Qxf4 Bxf4 22. Bf3 {White has annoying pressure on b7 , but Black should be able to hold without much difficulty thanks to the bishop pair.}) 9. d4 {The first player avoids a little trap by sacrificing a pawn. Analysis indicates that Black should proceed with caution.} (9. exd6 $6 {would be a slight mistake due to the intermediate} e5 $1) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nf5 ({The only move for Black.} 11... dxe5 $2 12. Qxe5 {would be a disaster since Black cannot properly develop due to the pressure on g7 .}) 12. Qd2 dxe5 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8 14. O-O-O+ Kc7 {By moving forward, Black's king covers the critical d6 -square. However, the king is a bit more vulnerable here.} 15. g4 Ne7 (15... Nh4 $6 16. Ne4 f6 17. g5 $1 {⩲ In general this is what White wants to achieve in this line: Pushing g5 without any complications!}) 16. Bg2 Ng6 17. h4 Nf4 18. Bf3 Be7 19. Kc2 {White's compensation for the pawn is evident, as Black find it difficult to complete his development.} Bd7 ({If} 19... f6 {White can attack Black's pawn chain with} 20. g5 $1 Rg8 21. Rhg1 {and Black is lacking a good move to relieve the pressure.}) {After 19... Bd7 White can choose} 20. Ne2 ({which is even stronger than gaining the material back with the simple} 20. Bxb7 {.}) *

