o look for an edge.}) 6... Ng4 7. h3 Nh6 8. Nc3 d6 (8... Nf5 {tries to fight against White's d4 push. Now a different approach is called for:} 9. Bd3 Nfd4 10. Ne4 d5 $1 {Now the game gets a little sharper. Some wild tactics will occur and White needs to be prepared for them.} 11. exd6 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 f5 13. Nxc5 Qxd6 14. b4 {The only move, but it is enough to save the day.} Nxb4 15. a3 Nc6 (15... Nxd3+ $2 16. Nxd3 {with important control over the e5 -square.}) 16. Nb3 Ne5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5+ 18. Be2 Bd6 19. d4 Qf4 20. c5 Bc7 21. Qxf4 Bxf4 22. Bf3 {White has annoying pressure on b7 , but Black should be able to hold without much difficulty thanks to the bishop pair.}) 9. d4 {The first player avoids a little trap by sacrificing a pawn. Analysis indicates that Black should proceed with caution.} (9. exd6 $6 {would be a slight mistake due to the intermediate} e5 $1) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nf5 12. Qe4 {White is not obliged to sac a pawn and go for the endgame. True, by defending the e5 -pawn we will lose at least one tempo with the queen, but that is perfectly affordable.} dxe5 13. Qxe5 b6 ({The hasty} 13... Bd6 $6 {is not ideal for Black, since White now has} 14. Qe4 {and Black faces issues with the c8 -bishop. Most likely the b7 -pawn has to be sacrificed, after which White gets an advantage. For example:} Bd7 15. Qxb7 Rc8 16. Ne4 $1 O-O 17. Nxd6 Qa5+ 18. b4 Nxd6 19. bxa5 Nxb7 20. Bc3) 14. Rd1 Bd6 15. Qe4 Ra7 {Warning: From this point on a long forced line appears.} 16. Bd3 Bb7 17. Qe2 Bxg2 18. Rg1 Nd4 (18... Bxh3 $4 19. Qf3 {and the bishop gets trapped in the corner.}) 19. Qg4 Nf3+ {At first sight it seems that White has made an oopsie. The reality is a little different though.} 20. Ke2 Nxg1+ 21. Rxg1 Bb7 22. Qxg7 Rf8 23. Ne4 f5 24. Nf6+ Rxf6 25. Qxf6 Qxf6 26. Bxf6 {White has the better chances in this endgame due to the activity of his rook, whereas its counterpart on a7 needs some time to get into the game.} *

