o look for an edge.}) 6... Ng4 7. h3 Nh6 8. Nc3 d6 (8... Nf5 {tries to fight against White's d4 push. Now a different approach is called for:} 9. Bd3 Nfd4 10. Ne4 d5 $1 {Now the game gets a little sharper. Some wild tactics will occur and White needs to be prepared for them.} 11. exd6 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 f5 13. Nxc5 Qxd6 14. b4 {The only move, but it is enough to save the day.} Nxb4 15. a3 Nc6 (15... Nxd3+ $2 16. Nxd3 {with important control over the e5 -square.}) 16. Nb3 Ne5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5+ 18. Be2 Bd6 19. d4 Qf4 20. c5 Bc7 21. Qxf4 Bxf4 22. Bf3 {White has annoying pressure on b7 , but Black should be able to hold without much difficulty thanks to the bishop pair.}) 9. d4 {The first player avoids a little trap by sacrificing a pawn. Analysis indicates that Black should proceed with caution.} (9. exd6 $6 {would be a slight mistake due to the intermediate} e5 $1) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nf5 12. Qe4 {White is not obliged to sac a pawn and go for the endgame. True, by defending the e5 -pawn we will lose at least one tempo with the queen, but that is perfectly affordable.} Bd7 {Trying to make use of the positioning of the white queen.} 13. Qxb7 {Taking up the gauntlet. Other tries would not produce promising results.} dxe5 14. O-O-O Rb8 15. Qxa6 Nd4 {Black has sacrificed all the queenside pawns and has all the files and diagonals at his disposal for an attack, but White's a2 - b3 - c4 chain looks very solid at the moment.} 16. Nb5 (16. Ne4 {leaves the a2 -pawn undefended, and this has its consequences:} Be7 17. Nd6+ Kf8 18. c5 Ra8 19. Qb7 Rxa2 20. Bc4 {with an unclear game.}) 16... Bxb5 {Only move.} 17. cxb5 Bc5 ({Again the only move. After} 17... Ra8 $4 18. Rxd4 $1 exd4 19. Qc6+ Ke7 20. Kb1 {White has way too many pluses in this position: Three passers, opponent's weak king and undeveloped kingside.}) 18. Kb1 ({Creating a situation with opposite colored bishops with} 18. Bxd4 {only helps Black in this position:} Bxd4 19. Qc6+ Ke7 20. Kb1 Qa5 21. Rxd4 $5 (21. Qc1 Rhc8 22. Bc4 Qb4) 21... Qe1+ 22. Kc2 exd4 23. Qc5+ Ke8 24. b6 Qc3+ 25. Qxc3 dxc3 26. Kxc3 Rxb6 27. b4 {The game should end in a draw with correct play, but I guess White's chances are preferable thanks to those two guys on the queenside.}) 18... O-O 19. Rc1 {A clear-cut solution! White must be ready to give up the queen.} ({Play might continue Ra8 Rxc5 Rxa6 bxa6} 19. Qb6 {Rxe5} Nc6 {Rg5 f6 Rb5} 20. Qa6 {Bc4 . We have reached a very original position after an almost forced series of moves. White does not risk much here, as the two passers and the bishop pair guarantee at least an equal game.}) *

