1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 a6 {By playing this move Black eliminates all variations connected with Bb5 . There are really not so much downsides to this wing move, as the move ... a6 is necessary and useful on many occasions in the Sicilian.} 4. Nf3 d6 (4... e6 {transposes to the line 3... e6 and 4... a6 , which is analyzed in the previous chapter.}) 5. d4 {Since White no longer has the option to play Bb5 , the most logical continuation is to play in 'Open Sicilian' style.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bd7 {It makes sense for Black to play this move, as it keeps the knight over-protected. The idea is capturing back with the bishop in case an exchange occurs.} 7. c4 {Had Black played 6... Nf6 first, this would not have been possible. Throughout the course (and in many master games) we see that White usually does enter the 'Maroczy Bind' whenever he is presented a chance.} Nf6 8. Nc3 g6 9. Be2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rc1 {This is a standard Maroczy position in which White enjoys a comfortable space advantage. One of the best ways to treat this position is to place a knight on d5 at the right moment. A few preparatory moves such as Bf3 - Qd2 - Rfd1 won't hurt. In the meantime, Black will try to accomplish the ... b5 break so White must watch out for this as well. The position is balanced according to the engines, but playing with a space advantage may come in handy in the future.} *

