1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 a6 {By playing this move Black eliminates all variations connected with Bb5 . There are really not so much downsides to this wing move, as the move ... a6 is necessary and useful on many occasions in the Sicilian.} 4. Nf3 d6 (4... e6 {transposes to the line 3... e6 and 4... a6 , which is analyzed in the previous chapter.}) 5. d4 {Since White no longer has the option to play Bb5 , the most logical continuation is to play in 'Open Sicilian' style.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Nxc6 {This capture is not forced. However, by taking on c6 White can reach a very safe and risk-free endgame.} (7. Nc3 {There is nothing wrong with this natural move.} Bd7 8. Qd2 e6 9. O-O-O b5 10. f3 Be7 11. g4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qc7 13. Kb1 O-O {⩲ A typical Sicilian fight with a strange twist. I meant the b2 -bishop of course! White has better prospects thanks to the safer king and the dangerous battery along the long diagonal.}) 7... bxc6 8. e5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bxe5 Bf5 ({With} 10... Nd5 {Black immediately wants to set up a strong center with ... f6 and ... e5 .} 11. Nc3 f6 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Bc3 e6 14. Ba5+ Ke8 15. O-O-O {⩲}) 11. Na3 {White has less pawn islands and a better king, which means White is on top!} *

