1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 a6 {By playing this move Black eliminates all variations connected with Bb5 . There are really not so much downsides to this wing move, as the move ... a6 is necessary and useful on many occasions in the Sicilian.} 4. f4 {Supporting the b2 bishop as expected. 4. f4 is the most common move in master's practice.} d6 5. Nf3 Bg4 {The following interesting idea was applied in one of the games. Black aims to shut the b2 -bishop down by making ... e5 possible. As we shall see, this plan does not fully achieve its aim.} 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e5 8. Bc4 Nf6 9. O-O Nd4 10. Bxd4 cxd4 (10... exd4 $4 11. e5 {is game over.}) 11. c3 {Trying to get the knight into the game by attacking Black's center.} Be7 12. cxd4 Qb6 13. Kh1 Qxd4 14. Nc3 {White is slightly better due to his better development and better bishop. Opening up the f-file and placing the knight on d5 to pressurize the f7 -pawn might be the best plan.} *

