1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {Black does not mind having his knight chased. Instead, followers of this particular line encourage their opponent to do so, as the e5 -pawn will be targeted later. Similar ideas can be seen in the Alekhine Defence or the Sicilian Alapin.} 4. e5 {The most principled!} (4. Nc3 {is the 'unambitious' alternative and was not played as frequently as 4. e5 . Play could continue} e6 5. Nf3 d5 6. Bb5 (6. e5 $6 Nd7 7. Bb5 Qc7 {is not advisable as Black can easily target the e5 -pawn.}) 6... Bd7 7. exd5 {The best option is to steer the game into 'isolated pawn' territories.} exd5 8. O-O Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Ne2 O-O 11. Nexd4 {It's a matter of taste, but we are guessing that many players would prefer White here. The position is balanced and most of the 'book knowledge' of isolani is still valid: White should try to exchange as many pieces as he can in order to exploit the 'weak' d5 -pawn. Black, on the contrary, must rely on active piece play.}) 4... Nd5 (4... Ne4 $2 {An unfortunate square for the knight. This move unnecessarily puts the knight in a very unstable place.} 5. Nf3 f6 6. Be2 d5 7. O-O fxe5 8. Nxe5 Nf6 9. Re1 {The backward e-pawn will be a huge problem for Black for many moves to come!}) 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bb5 {By now we know that this bishop sortie is typical. Black is forced to defend this knight or else his pawn structure will take a huge hit.} Bd7 7. exd6 e6 8. Nc3 {White has completed the development of the light pieces. Furthermore, Black experiences a slight discomfort due to the pressure on g7 .} Nf6 (8... Bxd6 {After the immediate capture on d6 , White can win a pawn but it is not as tasty as it may seem.} 9. Ne4 (9. Nxd5 {is the start of a forced line which ends in equality:} exd5 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Bxc6 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 Bxc6 14. Be5 Bb5+ 15. d3 Bxe5 16. Nxe5 f6 17. a4 Ba6 18. Nf3 Rxg2 19. Rhg1 Rxg1 20. Rxg1 Kf7) 9... Be7 10. Bxg7 Rg8 11. Bb2 f5 12. Ng3 Nf4 $1 {Black certainly has good compensation for the sacrificed pawn. White has to castle short and show some defensive skills.}) 9. d4 Bxd6 10. dxc5 {Clearing up the a1 - h8 diagonal is one of the key concepts of the whole system. During your games with the 2. b3 Sicilian, many similar situations may occur, and White must show precision to provide a good future for the b2 -bishop.} Bxc5 11. O-O O-O 12. Bd3 {This piece has completed its mission on b5 and now aims for the opponent's king. White has good middlegame prospects. The so called 'Horwitz Bishops' (a chess term for two bishops aggressively placed on adjacent diagonals) will increase their power if White can manage to dismantle the knight on f6 .} *

