1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 d5 {It is too early for this move, and the downside can be seen at first glance: Black's queen has to enter the game at a very early stage and lose a tempo.} 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe5+ {Now White faces a choice: To exchange queens, or complicate matters and try to take advantage of the intruder!} 6. Be2 (6. Qe2 {is seen in the model game Kramnik-Inarkiev .}) 6... Bg4 {Forced. Otherwise White gets in Nf3 for free.} 7. f4 Bxe2 8. Ngxe2 Qc7 9. O-O O-O-O ({In case Black decides on short castling with} 9... Nf6 {, White has a strong way to punish this:} 10. d3 e6 11. f5 $1 Be7 12. fxe6 fxe6 13. Qe1 {when Black cannot castle kingside just yet due to White's powerful reply Nf4 .}) 10. Nb5 Qd7 11. Nec3 {With the deadly threat of Na4 !} a6 (11... Kb8 {is nice prophylaxis, but after} 12. Ne4 e6 13. Rf3 $5 {intending Rd3 , White has the lead in development plus nice prospects for an attack. For instance} Nge7 14. Rd3 Nd5 15. c4 a6 16. cxd5 axb5 17. d6) 12. Na3 ({Practically speaking, this position is a huge challenge to play as Black. If b5 then} 12. Ne4 {is strong. Black's lack of development plays a big role in his problems.}) *

