1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e5 {Black has supported this pawn push with 2... Nc6 and now executes it. More often than not, we will find ourselves in a struggle where Black tries to shut down the b2 -bishop in this fashion. Right at this moment, White should plan for the future and play for f2 - f4 ideas to free the main guy.} 4. f4 {Applying our main plan immediately is a bit in the style of the King's Gambit. It is not certain whether White will be able to regain this pawn, but on a positive note, Black's army is caught unprepared and Black has to enter the complications.} exf4 (4... d6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. fxe5 Nxe4 7. Bb5 d5 {is a transposition to the following line : 1. e4  c5 2. b3  Nc6 3. Bb2  d6 4. Bb5  e5 5. f4  Nf6 !? 6. fxe5  Nxe4 7. Nf3  d5 .}) 5. Nf3 {Developing in King's Gambit style is a serious alternative, and the positions are reminiscent of the 4. Bb5 line. However White is not forced to transpose into that variation.} Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bc4 d6 8. Qe2 {Due to position's uncompromising nature, White prepares long castling. It is appropriate to point out that White was able to castle short as well:} (8. O-O O-O 9. d3 a6 10. a4 Ne5 11. Qd2 Ng6 {Black needs to hold on to his extra pawn. Otherwise his whole strategy might collapse.} 12. Nd5 {White won't be able to capture the f4 -pawn Therefore creating play in the middle of the board is the best chance.} Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Rb8 14. d4 {With such a strong bishop on d5 White must seek to bring some help and strengthen the attack.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. g3 {Arguably the most critical move in the variation. Both sides are eager to launch their own attack and White is faster when it comes to 'opening lines'.} fxg3 11. Rdg1 Bg4 12. Qe3 {This is a type of position which we must play without taking the engine's evaluation too seriously. White's whole army is stationed for a king hunt.} *

