1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e5 {Black has supported this pawn push with 2... Nc6 and now executes it. More often than not, we will find ourselves in a struggle where Black tries to shut down the b2 -bishop in this fashion. Right at this moment, White should plan for the future and play for f2 - f4 ideas to free the main guy.} 4. f4 {Applying our main plan immediately is a bit in the style of the King's Gambit. It is not certain whether White will be able to regain this pawn, but on a positive note, Black's army is caught unprepared and Black has to enter the complications.} exf4 (4... d6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. fxe5 Nxe4 7. Bb5 d5 {is a transposition to the following line : 1. e4  c5 2. b3  Nc6 3. Bb2  d6 4. Bb5  e5 5. f4  Nf6 !? 6. fxe5  Nxe4 7. Nf3  d5 .}) 5. Qf3 {Attacking the pawn right away is for those who do not like 'long-term sacrifices'.} Qh4+ {This greedy check can only be beneficial for White.} 6. g3 fxg3 7. hxg3 Qe7 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. O-O-O d6 10. Nd5 {We should choose the most dynamic option here, as Black is about to be ambushed. Opening the e file (although it will be blocked immediately by the black knight) is the way to go.} Nxd5 11. exd5 Ne5 12. Qf4 Bd7 13. Nf3 {Black's position irritates the eye even at a short glance. White prepares d4 while Black's king is still looking for a safe shelter.} *

