1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e5 {Black has supported this pawn push with 2... Nc6 and now executes it. More often than not, we will find ourselves in a struggle where Black tries to shut down the b2 -bishop in this fashion. Right at this moment, White should plan for the future and play for f2 - f4 ideas to free the main guy.} 4. Bc4 d6 5. Ne2 {Developing the knight to e2 is consistent with our main plan: Pushing f4 at the right moment!} Nf6 6. d3 {A committal move, considering our light-squared bishop gets semi-trapped on c4 .} a6 7. a4 Rb8 8. O-O (8. Nbc3 {To prevent Black's expansion on the queenside with b5 .} g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. f4 O-O 11. Qd2 {By playing 6. d3 this move became possible.} Bh6 12. Qe1 Ng4 13. Qg3 {White's threat is to push f5 , so Black's reply is more or less forced.} exf4 14. Nxf4 {One of our typical positions where we rely on the potential of the b2 -bishop and concentrate most of our forces on the opponent's king.}) 8... b5 9. axb5 axb5 10. Bd5 Nb4 11. c4 Be7 12. Na3 {This square is a bit better than c3 for the knight. The idea is play the knight to c2 to get rid of its counterpart on b4 .} O-O 13. Nc2 Nxc2 14. Qxc2 Qb6 15. f4 {White should show flexibility in this particular position, as an assault on Black's king will no longer be possible. Controlling the a-file is a small trump, but playing on both wings is on the agenda.} *

