{White's threat is to attack the lone king by h4 . Black can balance the game by applying a central approach with d5! . Then White has a choice: A: The computer gives a line which quickly leads to a repetition of moves: c3 Qa5 cxb4 Qxa3 Qe5+ Rf6 Qxe7+ Rf7 Qe5+ Rf6= . B: h4?! is an interesting try. As we have the option of analyzing every position in the opening we can detect the exceptional situations. As a rule of thumb, playing on the wing while the center is open is risky. Qa5 h5 N8c6! Fully ignoring White's attack. Qxa3?? jumps into disaster: hxg6 hxg6 Qe5+ Rf6 Qxe7+ Rf7 Rh7+ Kxh7 Qxf7+ Kh8 Nf3+- with the threat of -- Qf8+ Kh7 Ng5# . hxg6 hxg6 Qh4 Bf5 Qh6+ Kf6 g4 Bxg4 Qh4+ Kf5!? This inhuman move keeps the game going, but I doubt it can be found over the board. Kg7 Qh6+ is a draw by perpetual check. f3 Bh5 Nh3 Ke6 Ng5+ Kd7 Nxf7 Qxa3 c3! Nc2+ Kf2 Nxa1 Qf4 Rf8 The only move. Bh3+ Ke8 Nd6+! exd6 Re1+ Ne5 Rxe5+ dxe5 Qxe5+ Kf7 Be6+ Ke8 Bh3+ is another perpetual. We should warn the audience that this line is super sharp and any second rate move that has a surprise value by Black or White will lead to a totally different path. Be prepared!} 1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nf6 ({Black attacks the e4 -pawn immediately. This particular line has some similarities with the Alapin Sicilian ( e4 c5 c3} 2... Nf6 {), but with few key differences. First of all, White has the (most natural) c3 -square still available for his b1 -knight. The bishop quickly comes into play via b2 . Playing c4 in one move could be an option in the future. The only downside (compared to the Alapin) is that White might find it difficult to support the e5 -pawn in some situations.}) 3. e5 Nd5 4. Bb2 g6 {This is Black's main reply and is the topic of this chapter. Black immediately creates tension along the long diagonal and aims to eliminate the e5 -pawn. White must take drastic measures, since defending this pawn won't be easy.} 5. Qf3 {Among master games the queen move and the bishop sortie (5. Bc4 ) are the most popular moves. We must add that this line is fairly new and our sample size is limited.} (5. h4 {is another idea, which was tried without success by Morozevich:} Bg7 6. h5 d6 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Qe2 O-O 9. hxg6 fxg6 10. Qc4 dxe5 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ne2 Be6 13. Qh4 h6 14. Qg3 Bf5 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Qxe5 Qd6 17. Qxd6 exd6 18. d3 Rae8 19. Kd2 Bxd3 20. cxd3 Rxf2 21. Re1 Rxg2 22. a3 h5 23. Ra2 h4 24. Nbc3 Nxc3 25. Kxc3 h3 26. Nf4 Rxe1 27. Nxg2 h2 28. Nxe1 h1=Q 29. Re2 Kf7 30. Nc2 Qh8+ 31. Kd2 Qb2 32. b4 cxb4 33. axb4 g5 34. Re4 d5 35. Re3 d4 36. Rg3 Kg6 37. Kd1 Kh5 38. Rf3 g4 39. Rf4 g3 40. Nxd4 g2 41. Ne2 Qxe2+ 42. Kxe2 g1=Q 43. Rc4 Qg2+ 44. Ke3 Kg6 45. Kd4 Kf6 46. Kc3 Ke6 47. Rc5 Kd6 48. Ra5 Qf2 49. d4 Qe3+ 50. Kc4 a6 {0-1 Morozevich,A (2683) -Shaposhnikov,E (2557) Sochi 2016}) 5... Nb4 {This move makes sense as it safeguards the knight with tempo. Interestingly enough, it has been tried very rarely. In practice, the majority of players have chosen 5... Nc7 . However, the engine does approve of the knight jump to b4 , and in today's chess it is highly likely that this move will gain new supporters rapidly.} 6. Na3 (6. e6 $2 {does not work due to} f6 7. exd7+ Bxd7 8. Qxb7 $4 N8c6 {when White's queen is trapped.}) 6... Bg7 7. e6 {Now is the correct moment for this little trick.} O-O 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. exf7 Rxf7 10. Qg3 *

