1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Bb2 Nc6 {Developing the knight first is not only more principled, but also much more flexible. Depending on White's answer Black can later choose to go into a g6 -system anyway, or go into a completely different direction. Let's see how it goes.} 5. Nf3 g6 {With this move order White's queen did not manage to land on f3 , so a totally new position is ahead of us.} 6. Bb5 (6. Bc4 {has been tried before, but that move is met by} Nf4 {with some complications which might favor Black. Therefore the straightforward 6. Bb5 is our recommendation.}) 6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {As we can see, White does not face any issues defending the central e5 -pawn in this variation. Black has to challenge this pawn at some point in order to get a normal game.} d6 (8... b6 9. Bxc6 dxc6 10. Nc3 Be6 11. d3 Qd7 12. Qd2 {White's next move (given Black plays a quiet move) will be Ne4 .}) 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. h3 {Not allowing the pin on g4 . The play revolves around the advanced pawn on e5 .} Bf5 11. d3 h6 12. Nc3 g5 13. Qd2 {White's slight superiority derives from the pawn structure. The knight maneuver Ne2 - Ng3 is called for.} *

