1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Bb2 d6 5. exd6 {Now White has pressure on g7 , which makes life a bit more difficult for Black. Developing the f8 -bishop and realizing short castling requires some work for him. In the meantime, White may try to look for gains while Black is busy solving this issue.} Qxd6 (5... exd6 $6 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. d4 Be7 9. Ne2 O-O 10. c4 Nf6 11. d5 {A space advantage and a well-placed piece on b2 are good reasons to consider White to be better here.}) 6. Na3 {Whenever we see the black queen its scope, the knight chooses the corner to develop. This way the b2 -bishop also continues to shine.} Nc6 7. Nc4 Qc7 8. Qh5 e6 (8... Nf6 $2 9. Qxc5) 9. Nf3 {Already the problems along the long diagonal make itself felt. How can Black castle safely?} g6 10. Qh4 Be7 11. Qg3 ({White has a draw in hand with} 11. Qh6 Bf8 12. Qg5 Be7 {etc., but he can also continue the game in this way.}) 11... O-O 12. O-O-O {With chances for both sides. White has the unusual idea to swap off the queens and then play h4 . This won't be a deadly attack, but rather a positional squeeze.} *

