1. e4 c5 2. b3 d6 {This move order makes a significant difference for the arising positions: Since Black did not place the knight on c6 , the bishop check on b5 can be met by ... Bd7 . This way Black can protect his pawn formation. Pushing e5 and kicking the knight away is also not an option now. This is completely a new ocean!} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. Nc3 {Pre warning: Time is running out for the f1 bishop. Few more moves and it will have to be placed (most likely) on d3 . This -of course- is a matter of style since the final positions do not differ much in engine evaluation.} a6 {Making Bb5 + impossible at once, and keeping the ... b5 advance in hand in case it is needed. This expansion on the queenside is one of Black's typical trumps in the Sicilian.} 5. d4 {Since the opportunity is presented, we better make use of it and get into Carlsen's setup.} cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 {The ideal place for the queen, not stepping on any bishop's foot (or in this case diagonal).} e6 8. O-O-O Qc7 9. Kb1 {Prophylaxis. Stepping aside with the king has to be done sooner or later.} b5 10. f3 Bb7 11. g4 h6 12. Nge2 Rc8 13. Bg2 {None of these moves are forced, but they are chosen to give you an idea of the specific line. White's chances will always be better, since the king on b1 is extra protected thanks to the fianchettoed bishop.} *

