1. e4 c5 2. b3 d6 3. Bb2 Nc6 {'Move order' does matter in chess! Already by now you must have realized some positions from earlier chapters look alike or are identical to the current position. True, there are more than several transpositions and similar pawn structures. However, with each new chapter we will delve into something new.} 4. f4 e6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Bb5 {is a transposition to the line 1. e4  c5 2. b3  d6 3. Bb2  Nf6 4. Nc3  Nc6 5. f4  g6 6. Bb5 which was examined in detail in the previous chapter.}) 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nc3 ({It's too early for an 'immediate action':} 6. e5 Nd5 7. g3 dxe5 8. Nxe5 Bd7 $5 9. Bg2 ({After} 9. Nxd7 {It will be too much of a challenge for White to hold on to his bishop pair advantage since Black has the ... Be7 - Bf6 maneuver. And yes the tactics do work for Black!} Qxd7 10. Bg2 Be7 11. Bxg7 Nxf4 $1 12. O-O (12. gxf4 $4 Rg8 {is a nasty skewer.}) 12... Rg8 13. Rxf4 Rxg7 14. Na3 O-O-O {= With chances for both sides. Entering these lines is ill advised, since White has better choices at the start.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Bc6 11. O-O h5 $1 {This is another reason why we should keep away from this variation as White.} 12. Na3 h4 13. Nc4 Qd7 14. Bb2 hxg3 15. hxg3 Bd6) 6... Be7 7. e5 {Waiting one move makes a huge difference! White controls more space in the middle of the board, so now this push makes more sense.} dxe5 8. fxe5 Nd5 9. Bb5 {An important move, denying the opponent the opportunity to play ... b6 - Bb7 .} Bd7 10. Ne4 a6 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nf4 13. d3 {White's biggest trump in the position is (once again) the bishop on b2 . If a rook lift ( Rf3 - Rg3 ) would be possible, then White would be enjoying the game a lot, but that is not easy to achieve. An alternative plan is to play Qd2 and then double rooks on the f-file.} *

