1. e4 c5 2. b3 d6 3. Bb2 e5 {A straight-forward approach! Black shows his intentions from the get-go and closes out our bishop.} 4. f4 {We know the f4 lines with Bb5 check included. Now it is a bit different as White has the option of developing the light-squared bishop to c4 .} Nc6 5. Nc3 {We want to keep the f3 -square available for the queen in case Black changes his mind and captures on f4 .} exf4 6. Qf3 Nd4 {Black should not stay passive after grabbing on f4 .} 7. Bb5+ Bd7 {With the idea of keeping the central knight on d4 , which also means that Black is indirectly protecting the pawn on f4 .} 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qd3 Ne7 {A flexible move, intending to go to c6 or g6 depending on the situation.} (9... Nf6 $6 {, developing the knight to its natural square, is not challenging for White at all:} 10. O-O-O Ng4 11. Qf1 $1 g6 12. Nge2 Bg7 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Nd5) 10. O-O-O O-O-O 11. Nge2 {Black's knight can no longer keep its central post after this move.} Nxe2+ (11... Nec6 $2 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Nd5 {with the strong positional threat of Bxd4 .}) 12. Qxe2 Rg8 (12... d5 $2 13. d4 $1 {±}) 13. Qf2 g5 14. g3 {This line show the positional drawbacks of capturing on f4 . White will eventually regain the pawn with a healthier formation.} *

