1. e4 c5 2. b3 g6 {Black, without wasting time, gets ready for the struggle on the long diagonal. This move seems a little odd at first sight because White has the first go along this diagonal, but Black has logical ways to parry the threats and get a normal game. Things get complicated quite quickly here.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. f4 {White includes this move before getting queen to f3 . The benefit of stepping forward with the f pawn is strengthening the scope of the b2 bishop as we already know.} Bg7 5. Qf3 d6 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {We haven't seen this capture in our database, and this is apparently not without a reason! The knight does not have much mobility on d7 , and thus this move surrenders the upper hand to White easily.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nge2 Rb8 10. g4 {Taking more space and launching an attack towards the king.} b5 11. h4 {White has a very strong attack, as two sample lines show:} ({A: h5? gxh5 Nxh5} 11. O-O-O {Ndf6 Rdg1} e5 {Rg5+- White can remove Black's defenders without any problems with Rdg1 - f5 and even possibly Ng3 .}) ({B:} 11. b4 {Nd1} a5 12. g5 Nh5 13. Ng3 Nxg3 14. Qxg3 {Bxb2 Nxb2} e5 15. f5 {Two sample coninuations that show how comfortable it can be to play as White after the g4 pawn push. One innocent looking move by Black (capturing on d7 with the knight) and here we are!}) *

