1. e4 c5 2. b3 g6 {Black, without wasting time, gets ready for the struggle on the long diagonal. This move seems a little odd at first sight because White has the first go along this diagonal, but Black has logical ways to parry the threats and get a normal game. Things get complicated quite quickly here.} 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. f4 {White includes this move before getting queen to f3 . The benefit of stepping forward with the f pawn is strengthening the scope of the b2 bishop as we already know.} Bg7 5. Qf3 d6 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Ne2 O-O 9. c4 {We are building our standard pawn formation where the central pawns remain on the light squares.} (9. O-O {is seen in the model game Nepomniachtchi-Carlsen .}) 9... Nc6 10. Nbc3 {And now Black can choose between two main approaches: To play on the wing or in the center.} a6 11. d3 b5 12. O-O (12. cxb5 $2 {The pawn can not be captured since} axb5 13. Nxb5 Nb4 14. Na3 Rxa3 15. Bxa3 Nc2+ {wins for Black.}) 12... Rab8 13. h3 e6 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. Rd2 {A prophylactic move that protects the b2 -bishop in advance.} Nd4 16. Qf2 Nd7 17. Kh1 {White's chances lie on the kingside. The knight maneuver Nd1 - Ne3 is called for.} *

