1. e4 c5 2. b3 b6 {Black follows in White's footsteps. However, the fianchetto does not have the same effect for Black, as the a8 - h1 diagonal is already occupied by the e4 -pawn. This is a rare line, but very playable nonetheless.} 3. Bb2 Bb7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. f4 g6 {Black basically had two ways to develop the bishop. This one looks a bit dubious due to the White's 'already-deployed' queenside.} 6. Qe2 Nd4 7. Qd3 {True, the queen is misplaced a bit here, but this situation is temporary.} Bg7 8. O-O-O Qc7 9. g3 (9. Nge2 {After several exchanges Black is presented the opportunity to equalize immediately.} Nxe2+ 10. Nxe2 c4 $1 11. bxc4 Bxb2+ 12. Kxb2 Rc8 13. Qd4 Qxc4 14. Qxh8 Qxc2+ 15. Ka3 Qc5+ 16. Kb2 Qc2+ {Draw by perpetual.}) 9... Nf6 10. Bg2 Rc8 11. Nge2 {White just needs to eliminate the strong piece on d4 , but unfortunately Black has ways to balance the game.} Ng4 12. Rdf1 ({Here} 12. Nb5 $5 {is an interesting exchange sacrifice which might interest some players.} Nxb5 13. Bxg7 Rg8 14. Bb2 c4 15. Qxc4 Nf2 16. Qxc7 Nxc7 17. d3 Nxh1 18. Rxh1 {The power of the bishop pair surely compensates White for the exchange, but not more than that.}) 12... c4 {The start of a long forcing line.} 13. Qxc4 Qxc4 14. bxc4 Rxc4 15. h3 Nxe2+ 16. Nxe2 Bxb2+ 17. Kxb2 Nf6 18. d3 Rb4+ 19. Ka1 {In this endgame, the players have equal chances. White should try to advance on the kingside and capture more space.} *

