1. e4 c5 2. b3 b6 {Black follows in White's footsteps. However, the fianchetto does not have the same effect for Black, as the a8 - h1 diagonal is already occupied by the e4 -pawn. This is a rare line, but very playable nonetheless.} 3. Bb2 Bb7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. f4 e6 6. Nf3 a6 {A useful waiting move (as this move is in most Sicilians), wanting see White's next. Depending on the reply Black may choose to plya a system with ... d5 .} 7. g3 d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. Bg2 Nf6 10. Ne5 {It is vital to start with this move to have an extra option, namely g4 !} Be7 11. g4 ({Play might continue Nxe5 fxe5} 11. Ne4 Nxe4 {dxe4} 12. O-O Bg5 13. Bc3 b5 {e6 O-O exf7+ Rxf7 Rxf7 Kxf7} 14. Qe2 {and now Black must walk the following path, or else he is in trouble:} b4 {Be5 Qxd2 Qf1+ Ke8 Re1∞ with a very complicated position in which White is trying to bust the lone king. Engines always find a way out for Black, and thus say that the position is 'equal'. However, we doubt that this evaluation means much in an over the board game.}) *

