1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 d6 4. Bb5 Bd7 5. f4 {Securing the diagonal of the bishop as well as gaining space in the center.} a6 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qe2 {There are two main approaches for White in this position. They are obviously short and long castling. Going for queenside castling looks very enjoyable, since White's king has an extra guard and White has the better attacking chances. However, the analysis show that this choice is quite risky and Black may get the upper hand with correct play.} (9. d3 {intends to castle short, as the e4 -pawn has to be protected first.} Be7 10. O-O b5 11. Qe1 O-O 12. f5 {This is a completely different story.}) 9... Be7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. d4 {Carlsen gets the setup which he made popular.} cxd4 {This is a gross mistake, giving White what he desires from the get-go. Sicilian players often make this capture automatically, which makes this variation even more venomous. As we already know, Black should have continued with an expansion on the queenside.} (11... b5 $1 {And now 12.e5 and dxc5 are the main options.} 12. e5 (12. dxc5 b4 13. Na4 Nxe4 14. Ne5 Bd5 15. Rxd5 exd5 16. Nc6 Qd7 17. Nxb4 dxc5 18. Nb6 Qe6 19. N4xd5 Bd8 20. Re1) 12... Nd5 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. c4 bxc4 16. bxc4 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qe8 18. Qe4 $1 {and the danger is minimal for White.}) 12. Nxd4 Qc7 13. g4 {Of course! Otherwise, what would've been the point of White's entire set-up? Now the World Champion gets a very good version of the 'opposite side castling Sicilian' with a safe king and a faster attack. What more would one ask for from an opening line?} Rfe8 (13... d5 {The only way to continue fighting. Chess principles apply: 'Answer a wing attack with a counter in the center'.} 14. e5 Ne4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. f5 Bc5 {and now White has two choices: Either to take the pawn and accept reversed colored bishops or keep the tension and continue attacking.} 17. Rhe1 (17. fxe6 Bxd4 18. exf7+ Rxf7 19. Bxd4) 17... Bd5 18. Kb1 b5 19. h4) 14. g5 Nd7 15. h4 b5 16. g6 {The difference between how far White and Black have developed their respective attacks is enormous. Carlsen goes for the thematic 'opening of the lines' sacrifice. Going into detail for the rest of the game is not needed as White's opening strategy was a huge success. Also, both sides were already getting short of time and some mistakes were committed. But let's not forget: the theory of this line is not yet well known, and Black's 11th move is critical. We are confident that, as times passes by, the players behind the black pieces will improve their play in this line. Therefore, one has to think twice to castle long in this specific variation.} hxg6 17. h5 Bf6 18. hxg6 fxg6 19. e5 {In rapid play these types of up and downs are very normal. We were interested in the opening and middle game phase where we got to see the attacking ideas. After} (19. Nxc6 $1 Bxc3 20. Bxc3 Qxc6 21. Rd3 Rac8 22. Rg3 Nf8 23. Qh2 {Black can no longer defend himself.}) 19... Bxh1 20. exf6 Bb7 (20... b4 $1 21. Nxe6 bxc3 22. Rxh1 cxb2+ 23. Kxb2 Qa5 $1 24. fxg7 Kf7 {This inhuman computer line is just for informational purposes.}) 21. fxg7 Nc5 22. Ndxb5 (22. Rg1 Qxg7 23. Kb1 $1 {Running away from Qh6 check and threatening to take on b5 with one of the knights.} Qxd4 24. Rxg6+ Kf7 25. Nxb5 Qd5 26. Nxd6+ Ke7 27. Be5 Rg8 28. Rh6 Rg1+ 29. Kb2 Rh1 30. Rg6 Rh7 31. f5 {Another fun line which has little importance!}) 22... axb5 23. Nxb5 Qe7 24. Nxd6 Red8 25. Be5 Rxd6 {After} (25... Bd5 26. Qf2 Rxd6 27. Qxc5 Rd7 28. Qxe7 Rxe7 29. a4 Rxg7 30. Bxg7 Kxg7 31. c4 {White has some chances for survival.}) 26. Rxd6 Rxa2 27. Qh2 {This time Carlsen does not let it slip.} Ra8 28. f5 Qg5+ 29. Kb2 Qxf5 30. Qh8+ Kf7 31. g8=Q+ Rxg8 32. Qh7+ {Mate will follow in a few moves.} *

