1. e4 c5 2. b3 e6 3. Bb2 Nc6 4. f4 Nf6 {Gordievksy doesn't mind his knight getting chased. Now, in order for White to play for an opening advantage, he must push the e-pawn.} 5. e5 (5. Nc3 d5 6. e5 (6. Bb5 $6 {This move complicates matters a lot, but Black emerges on top if he knows what he is doing:} d4 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Na4 Nxe4 9. Qf3 Nf6 $1 10. Nxc5 Nd5 11. Bxd4 Nb4 12. c3 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Nc2+ 14. Kf2 Nxa1 {The uncertainty still continues, but Black should be able to organize his position by giving some material back.}) 6... Nd7 7. Nf3 a6 8. g3 Be7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O b5 {Black enjoys a good version of the French.}) 5... Nd5 6. g3 Be7 7. Nf3 b6 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O O-O {Both sides have fulfilled their obligations by developing in a normal fashion. Many more different setups could have been advised, but what's happening in the game is very logical so far.} 10. Na3 {Since this is an opening course, we need to take a look at other variations more in depth.} (10. c4 Ndb4 11. d3 {Threatening to kick away the knight with a3 .} d5 (11... d6 $6 12. a3 Na6 13. Nc3 {It turns out that Black's pressure on the e5 -pawn is not very important, as exchanging on e5 benefits White.} dxe5 14. fxe5 {With Ne4 to come, White has a pleasant position.}) 12. a3 Na6 13. Nc3 Nc7 {Black will search for counterplay in the center with the moves ... Qd7 and ... Rad8 , targeting the weak d3 -pawn/square. In return, White may reply by Qc2 and Rad1 and claim a tiny edge thanks to his spatial edge.}) 10... d6 11. Nc4 dxe5 12. Ncxe5 {After the exchange on e5 , the b2 -bishop's strength has increased. Play will be concentrated on the long diagonal from now on.} Bf6 13. Qe2 Ndb4 14. c3 {A difficult move to make! If necessary, the pawn could be pushed one square farther in the future. Therefore, solving the queenside issue for now is enough.} (14. d3 Rc8 {Getting ready for... Nd4 .} 15. a3 Nd5 16. Rae1 Ba8 17. h4 $5 Nde7 18. h5 {As we see in this line as well, White should make use of the kingside pawns.}) 14... Nd5 15. Ng4 Be7 {It is very, very understandable that Black tries to keep the bishop. However, other factors are more important in this position. This retreat also allows to show us how difficult it could be for Black to play against White's attack in practice.} (15... h5 $5 {is a brave choice that prevents further kingside expansion of White.} 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. Ne5 Qc7 18. c4 Rad8 {and after the inevitable exchanges of the minor pieces Black should be close to equality.}) 16. Ng5 (16. Nfe5 $1 {This move would have given White a considerable edge, as both c4 and f5 ideas hang in the air. Let's look at an interesting variation.} Nxe5 17. fxe5 Rb8 18. c4 Nb4 19. Nf6+ $1 Bxf6 20. exf6 Qd3 21. Qg4 Qg6 22. Qxg6 hxg6 23. fxg7 Rfd8 24. Bxb7 Rxb7 25. Bf6 {Black is not getting mated yet, as he has some resources to save the king, but White certainly has the upper hand with two monsters on g7 and f6 .}) 16... Bxg5 {Chess is interesting! Letting go of the bishop was the right approach a few moves ago, but now it is a mistake. Of course there is a big difference here, as the f-pawn changes its course.} 17. fxg5 Qxg5 18. c4 {The ever-creative Morozevich had foreseen that the dark-squared bishop together with all the forces would give him more than enough compensation for one pawn.} Nde7 19. Nf6+ {These rapid games (even the ones between world's best players) usually lack precision due to shortage of time. We find it beneficial to repeat: The mistakes that were made later in the game are not really our concern, as we are trying to build a complete opening repertoire.} (19. h4 $1 {would have made a huge difference.} Qg6 20. h5 Qg5 21. h6 {White made three moves in a row with the h-pawn and finishes the job.} f5 22. Qxe6+ Rf7 23. Rf4 $1 Nd8 24. Qe2 Bxg2 25. Qxg2 Ndc6 26. Ne5 Nxe5 27. Qxa8+ Rf8 28. Qg2 Nd3 29. hxg7 Rd8 30. Bc3 Nxf4 31. gxf4) 19... Kh8 (19... gxf6 20. Bxf6 Qh6 21. Bxc6 Nxc6 22. Rf4 {Looks super dangerous but Black has a way out.} Rfd8 $1 23. Raf1 Nd4 24. Rg4+ Kf8 25. Qe5 Ne2+ $1 26. Qxe2 Rxd2 27. Bg7+ Ke8 28. Bxh6 Rxe2 {One of those long computer lines, which players shouldn't be held responsible for not finding.}) 20. Ne4 Qg6 21. Nd6 Rab8 22. Rae1 {It was correct to take on b7 first.} Ba8 {Black had a chance to create his own play, but this is rather slow.} (22... Nd4 $1 23. Bxd4 Bxg2 24. Qxg2 cxd4 25. Nb5 Qc2 26. Nxd4 Qxa2 27. Qf2 {Black has stepped out of danger completely.}) 23. Rf4 {Taking some more space with tempo was winning on the spot:} (23. Be4 $1 Nd4 24. Bxd4 Bxe4 25. Qxe4 cxd4 26. Rxf7 $1 {Elegant way to close out things.} Rxf7 27. Qxg6 Nxg6 28. Nxf7+ Kg8 29. Ng5 e5 30. Nf3 {and Black loses a pawn as} Re8 {runs into} 31. Nxd4) 23... Nd4 24. Bxd4 cxd4 25. Bxa8 Rxa8 26. Qf3 Nf5 {The correct square, but the wrong piece! 26... f5 would have kept the balance.} 27. Nxf5 exf5 28. Rxf5 Rad8 29. Re7 Kg8 30. Rxa7 d3 31. Re7 Rd6 32. Kg2 h6 33. h4 h5 34. Qxh5 Ra8 35. Qf3 Rxa2 36. Re8+ {A fight with lots of ups and downs. However the opening phase is quite instructive, as it shows us the nuances of the line.} *

