1. e4 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. Nf3 g6 {One of Black's logical ways of continuing development. In the course we mainly examined lines where Black chose 5... e6 .} 6. Bc4 (6. Bb5 {is a strong alternative to the move that was played in the game. White keeps the option of exchanging on c6 .} Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 d6 (8... Nf4 $5 9. Nc3 Nd4 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne2 Bxe5 12. Nxf4 Bxf4 13. Bxd4) 9. Bxc6 {Now is the right moment.} bxc6 10. h3 Qd7 11. Nc3 Nf4 12. Re3 {The position is around equal, but Black has some issues with his pawn structure and thus has to play very precisely to keep the balance.}) 6... Nb6 7. Bb5 Bg7 8. Bxc6 {This is the right approach. Thanks to the advanced e-pawn White has a small plus.} bxc6 9. O-O c4 {Black has the two bishops and he won't mind getting a couple of pawns off the board, especially if one of those pawns is a doubled one.} 10. Re1 O-O 11. d3 {Forcing Black to make an immediate decision looked promising:} (11. Na3 cxb3 (11... Ba6 $6 12. Qe2 $1 c3 13. Qxa6 cxb2 14. Rab1 {and White wins the pawn.}) 12. axb3 d6 13. exd6 exd6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. h3 {White has a better game due to the fact he has less pawn islands.}) 11... cxd3 12. Qxd3 d6 13. c4 {This is the start of White's problems. Going into the endgame does not suit White's plans as Black gets a very good game with the bishop pair. Keeping the tension with} (13. Qe3 {was called for.} Bg4 14. Nbd2 Nd5 15. Qd4 Bf5 16. Qc4 {White retains some small pressure towards Black's pawns, although the position is roughly equal.}) 13... dxe5 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Nxe5 (15. Bxe5 f6 16. Bc3 e5 {looks fine for Black.}) 15... Bf5 16. f4 Nd7 {White has lost control, and now the bishops start to make their presence felt. The fact that the d-file is controlled by Black also makes things harder for White.} 17. Na3 (17. Nc3 Nxe5 18. fxe5 h5 19. Rad1 Bh6 {This was probably White's best chance to continue fighting.}) 17... Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Bf8 {Drawing attention to the misplaced knight.} 19. h3 h5 20. Nb1 (20. c5 {Creating an extra square for the knight won't help:} f6 21. Bb2 e6 22. Rac1 Kf7 {The issue of how the knight should get back into the game remains.}) 20... f6 21. Bb2 Kf7 22. Nc3 e6 23. Ne4 Be7 {Occupying the second rank immediately was a possibility:} (23... Bxe4 24. Rxe4 Rd2 25. Bc3 Rc2 26. Ba5 Bc5+ 27. Kh2 f5 28. Ree1 Bd6) 24. Re2 a5 25. Nc3 Rd3 26. Na4 Bb4 27. Rc1 Bd2 28. Rf1 Rad8 {Black is in full control. The rest of the game does not require further analysis. In the b3 Sicilian we are eager to give up the light-squared bishop in many lines, and what we saw in this sample game is very instructive. We got to witness one of Black's winning scenarios in case of a misplay by White in the opening.} 29. Bc1 Bb4 30. Be3 Rd1 31. Nb2 Rxf1+ 32. Kxf1 Bb1 33. Na4 Bd3 34. Nb2 Bxe2+ 35. Kxe2 e5 36. fxe5 fxe5 37. Nd3 Ke6 38. Bc1 Bc3 39. Nc5+ Kf5 40. Kf3 e4+ 41. Ke2 Bd4 42. Nb7 Ra8 43. Bd2 Bb6 44. Be3 Bxe3 45. Kxe3 Ke5 46. Nc5 Rd8 47. Nxe4 Rd1 48. Nd2 c5 49. Nf3+ Kf5 50. Nh4+ Kf6 51. Nf3 Ra1 52. a4 Rb1 53. Nd2 Re1+ 54. Kf2 Re8 55. Kf3 Ke5 56. Ke3 Kf5+ 57. Kf3 Rd8 58. Ke3 g5 59. Nf1 Rd1 60. Ke2 Rb1 61. Nd2 Rg1 62. Kf3 g4+ 63. hxg4+ hxg4+ 64. Kf2 Rc1 65. Ke2 Rc3 66. Kd1 Ke5 67. Ke2 Kd4 *

