{The following game is also a classical encounter, just like Kramnik-Inarkiev. Such games (in our opinion) have higher value than others, as in classical games the masters choose their moves more carefully as they have more time to evaluate and calculate.} 1. e4 c5 2. b3 d6 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. Bb5+ Bd7 (4... Nbd7 {is the main move that we analyzed in the theory section. Black blocks the check with the knight and hopes to chase the bishop later. This would mean White either loses a tempo or has to surrender the bishop pair. In the course we saw that this dilemma can be solved easily, and White has nothing to worry about after 4... Nbd7 .}) 5. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 6. d3 {Now White is left with the 'good bishop'.} g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O d5 {Everything was going more or less normally until this move. By allowing the e4 - e5 push Black commits an opening mistake.} (9... b5 {is one of the standard ways to continue. In Closed Sicilians Black usually makes the queenside his playground.} 10. Qe2 c4 $5 {Black is not forced to sacrifice a pawn of course, but in order to fully show the potential of the position it is worth taking a look.} 11. dxc4 bxc4 12. Qxc4 Rc8 13. Qe2 Qb6+ 14. Kh1 {After} (14. Bd4 Qc6 {Black regains the pawn no matter what.} 15. e5 Nd5 16. g3 dxe5 17. fxe5 Qxc2) 14... Qc6 15. e5 Nh5 16. Nd4 Qc5 {Black has very nice compensation for the pawn. In fact, it is very likely that the pawn will be taken back very soon and the balance will be restored.}) 10. Qe1 {The immediate pawn push would also have secured an edge:} (10. e5 Ne8 11. c4 $1 (11. Qe1 Nc7 12. Nbd2 b5 13. Qg3) 11... Nc7 12. Nc3 Nb8 13. Ba3 b6 14. d4) 10... d4 11. Qh4 {The queen is very threatening on this square. White may launch a kingside attack (the classical way of attacking is: f5 - Bc1 - Bh6 followed by Ng5 ) at any moment. Therefore, Moiseenko understandably looks for ways to counter those intentions.} e5 12. fxe5 Nh5 13. Qxd8 Rfxd8 14. Nbd2 {White has the semi open f-file for his rook and it is not easy for Black to create a stronghold on e5 .} Nxe5 15. a4 Nf4 16. Nc4 {Very strong and precise play by Short, move after move! White is applying the most effective plan to gain maximum out of this position. We must also add that Black is still within the 'margin of a draw' and not all is lost yet.} Nxf3+ (16... Nxc4 17. bxc4 Rd6 18. Ba3 Ne6 19. g4 {is an one-sided affair where only White can hope to win.}) 17. Rxf3 Ne6 18. Bc1 {Improving the bishop as not much was left to do in a1 - h8 diagonal.} b6 19. Bd2 Rab8 20. Be1 a6 21. Bg3 Rb7 22. h3 {White is not rushing things and is looking for ways to further strengthen his position. On the other hand, Black just needs to sit tight and defend with resilience.} f6 {Waiting and doing basically nothing is one of the hardest strategies to carry out correctly in chess. After} (22... Bf8 23. Raf1 Re8 24. a5 b5 25. Nb6 Bg7 26. Nd5 {White's position looks really good, but still there is lot to prove and achieve.}) 23. Bh4 {Missing an opportunity.} (23. a5 $1 b5 24. Nb6 {Once the knight heads for d5 , the negative sides of the move 22... f6 will be felt.} Nf8 25. Bh4 Rd6 26. Raf1 g5 27. Bg3 Rc6 28. Rf5 Ng6 29. Nd5 {Black's position should soon collapse like a house of cards.}) 23... Rf8 {Both grandmasters missed out on the queenside operation for one and a half move, but the ex-World Championship Challenger realizes his chances now and finishes the game.} (23... b5 {was the only chance, as White's threat of a5 is very annoying.} 24. axb5 axb5 25. Nd2 Re8 $1 26. Bxf6 Bh6 27. Nf1 Rbb8 {Black has some chances for half a point thanks to the active bishop on h6 .}) 24. a5 b5 25. Nb6 g5 26. Bg3 Kf7 27. Rf5 Rd8 28. Raf1 {Take a look at the difference between the health of pawn chains. It is not only the structural superiority; White's forces are perfectly aligned too.} Kg6 29. Nd5 Rf8 30. Bd6 Rff7 31. e5 {The finishing touch. Other moves also would have secured the victory. For instance:} (31. h4 h6 32. Be5 gxh4 (32... fxe5 33. Rxf7 Rxf7 34. h5+ Kxh5 35. Rxf7) 33. Bxf6 c4 34. Bxh4 Rfd7 35. Bg3) 31... fxe5 32. Rxf7 Rxf7 33. Ne7+ Rxe7 34. Bxe7 {After losing the exchange the Ukrainian grandmaster tried to put up as much resistance as he could, but the rook proved to be too strong. The lesson we learn from this example is how quickly things could change after Black's strategic error in the opening, namely the 9... d5 push.} h5 35. Kf2 Bf6 36. Bxf6 Kxf6 37. g3 h4 38. gxh4 gxh4 39. Rg1 Ng5 40. Rg4 Nxh3+ 41. Kf1 Nf4 42. Rxh4 Kg5 43. Rh8 Nd5 44. Ke1 Nb4 45. Kd1 Kf6 46. Rc8 Ke6 47. Rxc5 Kd6 48. Rc8 Nc6 49. Ra8 Nxa5 50. Rxa6+ Nc6 51. Kd2 Kc5 52. Ra8 Nb4 53. Rc8+ Kd6 54. Ke2 Nd5 55. Kf3 Nc3 56. Rxc3 dxc3 57. Ke4 b4 58. d4 exd4 59. Kxd4 Ke6 60. Kc4 Ke5 61. Kxb4 Kd4 62. Ka4 Ke3 63. b4 *

