1. e4 c5 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. Qf3 d6 5. Bb5+ Nbd7 6. Bxf6 {This is the main idea of this line: White surrenders the two bishops (both of them actually!) and ruins the pawn structure of the opponent. This leads to a doubled f-pawn which makes the life of the f8 -bishop harder, and a big hold on the d5 -square. Proceed with caution!} exf6 7. Nc3 a6 8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 9. Nge2 {White is heading for the d5 -square, since one knight controlling that square would not be sufficient.} (9. Qd3 {is the move we suggested for the course. The queen swing not only controls the central d5 -square but also puts pressure on d6 .}) 9... Bg7 10. Qg3 {Not the correct approach. Pressurizing d6 is an effective idea in this line, but White had to make a choice between these two plans: Either maneuver the queen or immediately head for the d5 -square with the knights. Combining both plans and trying to achieve both at the same time has downsides.} (10. Nf4 O-O 11. O-O Bc6 12. Nfd5 Re8 13. Rae1 (13. d3 $4 f5 {is a little trap which we should be aware of.}) (13. Qd3 {is a very interesting exchange sacrifice worth mentioning.} b5 14. Rae1 b4 15. Nd1 Bb5 16. Qf3 Bxf1 17. Rxf1 {Intending N1e3 with great control over the light squares.}) 13... b5 14. a3 Rb8 15. b4 {An interesting fight lies ahead between the knights and bishops.}) 10... Be6 (10... Bc6 {This choice would have made things extremely difficult for White as the jump 11. Nf4 is not possible now due to 11... f5 .} 11. O-O (11. Nf4 $2 f5 $1 12. exf5 Be5 13. Qe3 O-O 14. fxg6 hxg6 15. O-O Re8 16. Rae1 d5) 11... O-O 12. Rae1 Re8 13. Nf4 Re5 {and Black eventually will manage to insert .. .f5, tidy up his pawn structure and enjoy the bishop pair.}) 11. Nf4 {Now White is back on track.} O-O (11... f5 $2 {does not have the same power as White can eliminate one of the bishops.} 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. exf5 exf5 14. O-O O-O 15. Rae1 {White will soon occupy the d5 -square while the g7 -bishop stares into an empty diagonal.}) 12. O-O f5 13. Rae1 (13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. exf5 gxf5 {Being able to take back with the g-pawn is the main difference to the game. Note that Black did not have this opportunity a move earlier, as g7 was hanging.}) 13... Qd7 {Letting White accomplish the 'big dream'.} (13... Be5 $1 14. Qf3 Qh4 15. g3 Qg4 16. Qxg4 fxg4 17. Ncd5 Bxf4 18. Nxf4 b5) 14. Ncd5 Rae8 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Nh5 {Two strong moves in a row and the knights prove to be more diligent than the bishops.} Qd8 17. Nxg7 Kxg7 18. c4 Be4 {Passive defense is an option, but it doesn't change the evaluation of the position by much:} (18... f6 19. h4 $1 Re5 20. h5 Rfe8 21. Re3 b5 22. Rfe1) 19. Qc3+ f6 20. Nf4 Qd7 21. f3 Bc6 22. d4 Qf5 (22... Qf7 23. h4 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Re8 25. Re3 Kf8 26. dxc5 dxc5 27. Kf2 {White will keep torturing the opponent in this slightly better endgame without any risk.}) 23. Qd2 {White missed a tactic:} (23. Ne6+ $1 Rxe6 24. g4 Rxe1 (24... Qf4 25. Rxe6 cxd4 26. Qc1 Qxc1 27. Rxc1 Bxf3 28. Rxd6 Bxg4 29. Kf2) 25. gxf5 Rxf1+ 26. Kxf1 cxd4 27. Qxd4 Bxf3 28. Qxd6 Rf7 {Black can hope to create a 'fortress'.}) 23... Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Re8 25. Rxe8 Bxe8 26. g4 Qb1+ 27. Kg2 Bf7 28. dxc5 dxc5 29. Nd5 Qa1 {Black is defending fairly well, and the game should be drawn with correct play. Correct play and practice, these two words collide quite frequently. Of course not} (29... Bxd5 $4 {as} 30. cxd5 {would win easily:} Kf7 31. d6 Ke8 32. Qe3+ Kd7 33. Qe7+ Kc6 34. d7 Qxa2+ 35. Kg3) 30. Nc3 Be8 31. Qe3 Bf7 32. h4 b5 33. cxb5 axb5 34. Qxc5 Qe1 {The losing move.} (34... h5 $1 35. gxh5 (35. Qd4 hxg4 36. fxg4 b4 $1 37. Qxb4 {and only now} Qe1 {secures the draw.}) 35... gxh5 36. Qd4 Qb2+ 37. Kg3 Qa1 {It is very tough for White to make progress.}) 35. Ne4 Qxh4 36. Qxb5 h5 37. g5 Be6 38. Qb7+ Kh8 39. Qb8+ Kh7 40. Qc7+ Kg8 41. Qd8+ {We can make a summary here: This line of the b3 Sicilian is extremely sharp and risky. White easily gives Black the two bishops and looks for positional play. This is surely one of the most interesting and unbalanced variation out of the ones we examined.} *

