{When two elite players battle it out in the b3 Sicilian, the game automatically becomes our point of interest (even though this is an internet blitz game!) .} 1. b3 g6 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. e4 c5 {As we can see the game transposed into the opening line we are investigating. One hardly expects to get a Sicilian after 1.b3 isn't it?} 4. f4 Bg7 5. Qf3 d6 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Ne2 O-O 9. O-O (9. c4 {is the suggestion in our theory section, but there is nothing wrong with the game continuation either.}) 9... Nc6 10. d3 b5 (10... d5 $5 {This idea led Black into trouble in the Short-Moiseenko model game. However, here the situation is different: Black has better control over the center due to the placement of Nc6 and Qd7 . These two pieces make a perceivable difference.} 11. e5 Ne8 12. c4 dxc4 13. dxc4 f6 $1 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Nbc3 e5) 11. c4 b4 12. h3 {White's main idea is to advance on the kingside and create some targets, but in order to achieve this, first he must clarify the position on the other side of the board. This is not going to be easy, since Black has his trumps as well.} a5 13. a4 bxa3 {This is a blitz game, so intuition is the best guide of the players. Carlsen wants at least one open file on his turf. This is strategically correct, but there was another approach as well.} (13... e6 14. g4 (14. Nd2 $4 Nxe4) 14... Rad8 {Black is getting ready for ... d5 in case White over-pushes on the kingside.}) 14. Rxa3 Rab8 15. Bc3 {Now both sides have targets. White has to postpone (or cancel completely) his attack plans starting with g4 .} Ne8 16. Qe3 (16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. Nbc3 f5 18. Qe3 Ne6 19. Nb5 Nc7 20. Nec3 Ne6 21. Ne2 Nc7 22. Nec3 {A highly original move repetition: The dance of the knights for central squares is astonishing.}) 16... f5 17. exf5 gxf5 18. Bxg7 Nxg7 19. Nbc3 {So far both sides showed great understanding of the position (as expected from them) and we have a balanced struggle. The opening phase has ended (or did it end a few moves earlier?) and it's time to draw our conclusions: Black must be ready to strike back in the center or on the queenside whenever White marches forward with his kingside pawns. This variation is strategically very rich, and one single positional mistake could decide the fate of the game. It is advisable for White players to finish the development of the b1 knight first, and then decide how to continue based on the opponent's intentions. Due to the shortage of time, we find it meaningless to mark the remaining moves and give long suggestions. Hopefully we got what we wanted from the opening part.} Ne6 20. Nb5 Rf6 21. Rf3 Rg6 (21... d5 $1 22. Rg3+ Kh8 {It's a bit counter-intuitive not to block the check, but it works perfectly.} 23. Qf3 d4 24. Ra2 Ng7) 22. Rg3 Kf7 23. Kh2 Qd8 {This allows the white queen to change its position with gain of tempo.} 24. Qf3 Rc8 25. Qh5 Ng7 26. Qxh7 Rxg3 27. Kxg3 Qg8 28. Qxg8+ Rxg8 29. Kf3 {It is still not easy to convert with an extra pawn due to the passive position of the a3 -rook.} Ne6 30. Ra1 Kf6 (30... Rh8 $1 {Denying the very important g4 push was the best defense.}) 31. g4 Rh8 32. g5+ Kg6 33. Kg3 (33. Rh1 Nb4 34. d4 Nxd4+ 35. Nbxd4 cxd4 36. Nxd4 e5 37. Ne2 Nd3 38. h4 {and White retains some chances of victory.}) 33... Nb4 34. d4 (34. Rxa5 Nxd3 35. Ra7 Rh7 36. Nc7 Nxc7 37. Rxc7) 34... cxd4 (34... Nc2 $1 35. Rd1 cxd4 36. Nbxd4 Ncxd4 37. Nxd4 Nxd4 38. Rxd4 Ra8 39. Rd3 a4 40. bxa4 Rxa4) 35. Nbxd4 Nc5 36. Rxa5 {The game ended in a usual 'time scramble' mess.} Ne4+ (36... e6) 37. Kg2 Nc5 38. Rb5 Nbd3 39. b4 Ne4 40. Nxf5 Ne1+ 41. Kf1 Rxh3 42. Kxe1 Rh1+ 43. Ng1 Rxg1+ 44. Ke2 e5 45. Nh4+ Kh5 46. Nf3 Rg4 47. Ke3 Nc3 48. Rb6 Rxf4 49. Rxd6 Rxc4 50. Rh6+ Kg4 51. Rh4+ *

